[{"id":"VH217623","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><include href=\"../Passage/VH217587.qti.xml\" xmlns:xi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude\"></include></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The scenes depicted in the work are intended to convey the ancient Egyptian concept of</p>\n","rubricRef":"VH217623_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<div class=\"stimulus_reference\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents an ancient Egyptian painting. From left to right, the painting depicts a person with the head of a canine, and another person holding hands and walking towards the right. Next to them is a large scale. A smaller person with a canine head is kneeling below the scale to the right, while a composite animal with the head of a hippo is standing below the scale on the left. A person with the head of a bird is standing to the right of the scale, turned to the left. To the right of this figure is a person dressed in white and a person with the head of a raptor who are standing before another person seated on a throne. Two women stand behind the throne. In the upper part of the painting, there is a row of smaller figures seated in a row facing left. All the way to the left is a kneeling figure dressed in white with raised hands who is facing the seated figures.\" height=\"196\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VH217587.g04.png\" width=\"400\" /><span class=\"mandatory_credit_line\">© The Trustees of the British Museum / Art Resource, NY</span></div>\n</div>\n"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">justice and morality, by depicting the divine judgment of a mortal person’s life</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">mercy and forgiveness of sins, represented by Osiris granting absolution to believers</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">the cyclical nature of the cosmos, by showing Anubis overseeing the rebirth of the dead</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">the divine nature of the pharaoh, presented in his role as protector of order and stability</p>"],"answer":0}]